<doc id="457464" wikidata="Q884772" url="?curid=457464" title="Block matrix">
<text>In mathematics, a block matrix or a partitioned matrix is a matrix that is interpreted as having been broken into sections called blocks or submatrices.

Intuitively, a matrix interpreted as a block matrix can be visualized as the original matrix with a collection of horizontal and vertical lines, which break it up, or partition it, into a collection of smaller matrices. For example, the 3x4 matrix presented below is divided by horizontal and vertical lines into four blocks: the top-left 2x3 block, the top-right 2x1 block, the bottom-left 1x3 block, and the bottom-right 1x1 block.

:formula_1

Any matrix may be interpreted as a block matrix in one or more ways, with each interpretation defined by how its rows and columns are partitioned.

This notion can be made more precise for an formula_2 by formula_3 matrix formula_4 by partitioning formula_2 into a collection formula_6, and then partitioning formula_3 into a collection formula_8. The original matrix is then considered as the &quot;total&quot; of these groups, in the sense that the formula_9 entry of the original matrix corresponds in a 1-to-1 way with some formula_10 offset entry of some formula_11, where formula_12 and formula_13.

Block matrix algebra arises in general from biproducts in categories of matrices.
==Example==
The matrix

:formula_14

can be visualized as divided into four blocks, as 

:formula_15.

The horizontal and vertical lines have no special mathematical meaning, but are a common way to visualize a partition. By this partition, formula_16 is partitioned into four 2×2 blocks, as

:formula_17

The partitioned matrix can then be written as

:formula_18

==Formal definition==
Let formula_19. A partitioning of formula_20 is a representation of formula_20 in the form

:formula_22,

where formula_23 are contiguous submatrices, formula_24, and formula_25. The elements formula_26 of the partition are called blocks.

By this definition, the blocks in any one column must all have the same number of columns. Similarly, the blocks in any one row must have the same number of rows.

=== Partitioning methods ===
A matrix can be partitioned in many ways. For example, a matrix formula_20 is said to be partitioned by columns if it is written as

:formula_28,

where formula_29 is the formula_30th column of formula_20. A matrix can also be partitioned by rows:

:formula_32,

where formula_33 is the formula_34th row of formula_20.

=== Common partitions ===
Often, we encounter the 2x2 partition

:formula_36,

particularly in the form where formula_37 is a scalar:

:formula_38.
